Dutch Blitz Project Report

Olivia Martin

2022-12-07

Introduction. The purpose of this experiment was to determine what factors impact a players score in the game Dutch Blitz, as well as the importance of each factor. I identified four potential explanatory variables, covering the starting conditions, ending conditions, and duration of each game, and players.

The rules of Dutch Blitz can be found at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6n3VyC0ngY8&t=74s. The rules for this experiment deviated in the following ways: no Post Pile stacking was allowed, and the number of cards remaining in the Blitz Pile was not factored into the score. In this context, a game refers to one round of play rather than as many rounds as necessary to reach 75 points.

Data Collection. The data used in this experiment was collected from 30 games of Dutch Blitz. They were played by four subjects, whose names have been coded by the color of the deck they played with: red buggies, yellow buckets, blue plows, and green buckets. Games were played on November 29th, 2022, in two sets of 15 games each.

Variables.

  • ID: game ID. Each game created four cases, one for each players spread and score. This variable exists for data management purposes and is not for use in models.

  • time: duration of the game in seconds.

  • blitz: color alias of player that ended the game by emptying their Blitz Pile.

  • player: the color alias of the player to whom each cases spread and score belongs.

  • spread: the sum of the values of the four exposed cards in each players Post and Blitz Piles at the start of the game. If a players spread was below five or above 25, the player replaced one of the cards with a card from the Wood Pile until the spread fell within the target range.

  • score: the total number of cards played by each player in the game.

Exploration of Data.

blitz_data = read.csv("blitz_data.csv")
player_order = c('red', 'yellow', 'green', 'blue')

blitz_display = blitz_data %>% mutate(player = ordered(blitz_data$player, levels = player_order), blitz = ordered(blitz_data$blitz, levels = player_order))
player_colors = c('red', 'yellow', 'limegreen', 'dodgerblue')
blitz_display %>% ggplot(aes(x = player, y = score, fill = player)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = player_colors)

As we see here, Yellow generally scored the highest and Red the lowest. This trend is supported by the results of many games of Blitz, though based on past games I would have expected Green to fall more firmly between Blue and Red.

ggplot(blitz_display, aes(x = spread, y = score, color = player)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_manual(values = player_colors) +
  labs(title = 'spread vs. score')

At first, I assumed spread would have a strong impact on score because a lower spread ostensibly means a player has more playable cards early in the game. However, even when sorted by player, spread appears to be a very weak predictor of score, and may not be useful at all.

ggplot(blitz_display, aes(x = time, y = score, color = player)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_manual(values = player_colors) +
  labs(title = 'duration vs. score', x = 'duration of game (sec)')

Duration, as expected, does seem to have some effect on score when sorted by player. The relationship also seems to be somewhat linear.

Exploration of Models. In pursuit of the best model, I examined the individual impact of each of the potential explanatory variables. Here are the results:

Model Formula Parameters R2 p-value
score ~ player 4 0.31 <10-4
score ~ blitz 4 0.06 0.08
score ~ spread 2 0.06 0.4
score ~ time 2 0.19 <10-4

Based on this information, I would discount blitz and spread as explanatory variables. blitz does appear to have a tiny impact on score, but based on the p-value I cannot conclude that this result is repeatable; I suspect the impact is more to do with random chance.* player and time, and perhaps an interaction term between the two, will offer the best model given the available data.

*See Limitations for further notes on this subject.

Model Formula Parameters R2 p-value
score ~ player + time 5 0.50 <10-4
score ~ player * time 8 0.50 <10-4
score ~ player:time 5 0.47 <10-4
score ~ player + player:time 8 0.50 <10-4
score ~ time + player:time 5 0.47 <10-4

These calculations suggest that the interaction between player and time is not particularly significant, and the ANOVA table gives player:time a p-value of 0.86. Player and time seem to be the predominant factors in determining score, though the effect of the duration does not appear to vary by player.

Conclusion. Based on my exploration, the best model is score ~ player + time. The formula of best fit is score = 8.81 + 0.07time - 5.90playerred + 1.23playeryellow - 0.70playergreen. While this model only accounts for half of the variance, the information it does provide seems to align with information gleaned from casual observation. Yellow typically has the highest score, with Blue and Green close behind, and Red scoring five to seven points fewer than the rest of the players. Averaging across players, one card every roughly ten seconds also seems reasonable.

ggplot(blitz_display, aes(x = time, y = score, color = player)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(slope = 0.07, intercept = 2.91, size = 1, color = 'red', ) +
  geom_abline(slope = 0.07, intercept = 10.04, size = 1, color = 'yellow') +
  geom_abline(slope = 0.07, intercept = 8.14, size = 1, color = 'limegreen') +
  geom_abline(slope = 0.07, intercept = 8.81, size = 1, color = 'dodgerblue') +
  scale_color_manual(values = player_colors) +
  labs(title = 'final model', x = 'duration of game (sec)')

Limitations.

  • Number of players would likely also affect score (as well as time), but was not studied here.

  • There were some games wherein a certain color of card could not be played until well into the game; for example, in game 4, no red ones were played until second 61, making any red cards in the Blitz, Post, or Wood Piles ineffective. Further exploration or control of this variable might yield more specific results. For purposes of this report, such variation is considered an aspect of random chance.

  • According to official Dutch Blitz rules, the score is the number of cards played minus twice the number of cards remaining in the Blitz Pile at the end of play. This group does not adhere to that rule. Were it followed, I conjecture that blitz would be a useful explanatory variable.

  • According to official Dutch Blitz rules, Post Piles can be stacked under certain conditions. This group does not adhere to that rule, and introducing it for data collection would likely have warped the outcome. However, a more thorough study on this topic would likely need to incorporate that rule, and I suspect it would affect the outcome.

  • Players are comfortable with each other; results might vary depending on opponents.
